{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631287"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:25:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:25:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17362"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17362"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10052"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115147"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10052"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17362"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97155"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5487"},{"type":"tags","id":"7818"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23541"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23545"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115147"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the key assumption of a fixed-effect model in meta-analysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sample sizes must be equal across studies","Larger studies are always more accurate","Studies must use identical measurement methods","Effect sizes vary randomly between studies","All studies measure exactly the same effect size"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe fundamental assumption of a \u003Cstrong\u003Efixed-effect model\u003C/strong\u003E is that all included studies are measuring exactly the same true effect size, with any observed differences being due to sampling error alone. This assumes the studies are functionally identical and drawn from the same population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEffect sizes vary randomly between studies\u003C/strong\u003E describes the assumption of a random-effects model, not a fixed-effect model. \u003Cstrong\u003ELarger studies are always more accurate\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as while larger studies typically receive more weight in fixed-effect models, sample size alone does not guarantee accuracy. \u003Cstrong\u003EStudies must use identical measurement methods\u003C/strong\u003E is not the key assumption of the fixed-effect model, although methodological similarity is desirable. \u003Cstrong\u003ESample sizes must be equal across studies\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as studies can have different sample sizes and the model adjusts for this in the weighting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn practice, fixed-effect models are most appropriate when studies are very similar in their methods and populations. When studies are more heterogeneous, a random-effects model may be more appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A fixed-effect model assumes that all studies in a meta-analysis share one true effect size, with variations due only to sampling error.","Fixed-effect models are appropriate when studies are functionally identical and drawn from the same population.","The weight assigned to each study in a fixed-effect model is based primarily on sample size."],"references":["Motulsky H. Intuitive Biostatistics: A Nonmathematical Guide to Statistical Thinking. 4th ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press; 2017. Chapter 43; pg 457.","Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97155"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17362"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97155"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T13:55:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T13:55:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10052"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115147"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T13:30:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"gr